{
  "result": "Midnight at the laundromat is a cathedral of small cycles. The drums whisper and kneel, rinse and rise, tossing socks like pale birds startled from a hedge. Above the change machine, a corkboard lists lessons in crooked pushpins: babysitter needed, guitar for sale, cat missing, hope returning. I sit with a paperback, unread, and a lukewarm coffee growing a skin as thin as an unkept promise.\n\nPeople come in pairs, mostly. They argue softly about heat settings, about stains with histories: marinara, grass, engine oil, red wine that remembers a balcony. A man with a scar on his chin folds T-shirts with ceremonial care, smoothing each chest as if convincing the day ahead to behave. A child presses her ear to a front loader and declares it ocean. She is right; it sounds like a tide patient with the moon.\n\nOn the television bolted high, a game no one follows marches through commercials. Voices rise and fall, detergent bright and consequence light. I think of all the garments carrying the faint biographies of their owners: the elbow-polished sleeves, the knees that learned to pray to asphalt, the collars resigned to sweat and weather.\n\nWhen my cycle ends, the room applauds in clicks. I lift a warm avalanche into the plastic basket, mountain air trapped between towels. Outside, the parking lot hums its fluorescent hymn. I drive home with weather in the trunk, heat that will cool, order that will fray, and the knowledge that we will return for another absolution.",
